# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: crop-monitoring-remote
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] In agriculture, the **yield** is a measurement of the amount of a crop grown, or product such as wool, meat or milk produced, per unit area of land.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] The **seed ratio** is another way of calculating yields.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] Innovations, such as the use of fertilizer, the creation of better farming tools, and new methods of farming and improved crop varieties have improved yields.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] The higher the yield and more intensive use of the farmland, the higher the productivity and profitability of a farm; this increases the well-being of farming families.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] Surplus crops beyond the needs of subsistence agriculture can be sold or bartered.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] The more grain or fodder a farmer can produce, the more draft animals such as horses and oxen could be supported and harnessed for labour and production of manure.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] Increased crop yields also means fewer hands are needed on farm, freeing them for industry and commerce.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] This, in turn, led to the formation and growth of cities, which then translated into an increased demand for foodstuffs or other agricultural products.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] In 2025, around 1.7 billion people live in areas experiencing sizeable degradation-induced crop yield losses.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] Middle-income countries are the most affected, accounting for nearly 1 billion people, while in high-income countries, intensive input use sustains yields but masks degradation and increases environmental harm.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] Climate change is further compounding these pressures: a 2026 joint report by the FAO and the World Meteorological Organization (WMO) estimates that temperatures exceeding 25°C trigger significant yield losses, with cascading effects on harvests and food prices that can persist for up to a year.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] The units by which the yield of a crop is usually measured today are kilograms per hectare or bushels per acre.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] In Brazil, the customary unit of production of "sacks" is used, equivalent to 60 kilograms (132.277 pounds), and as a result production is measured in sacks per hectare.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] Long-term cereal yields in the United Kingdom were some 500 kg/ha in medieval times, jumping to 2000 kg/ha in the Industrial Revolution, and jumping again to 8000 kg/ha in the Green Revolution.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] Each technological advance increasing the crop yield also reduces the society's ecological footprint.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] Yields are related to agricultural productivity, but are not synonymous.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] Agricultural productivity is measured in money produced per unit of land, but yields are measured in the weight of the crop produced per unit of land.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] A yield is a 'partial measure of productivity', because it may fail to accurately measure the actual productivity of the farming operation by not including the totality of the inputs.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] The seed multiplication ratio is the ratio between the investment in seed versus the yield.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] For example, if three grains are harvested for each grain seeded, the resulting multiplication ratio is 1:3, which is considered by some agronomists as the minimum required to sustain human life.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] One of the three seeds must be set aside for the next planting season, the remaining two either consumed by the grower, or for livestock feed.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] In parts of Europe the seed ratio during the 9th century was merely 1:2.5, in the Low Countries it improved to 1:14 with the introduction of the three-field system of crop rotation around the 14th century.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] Seed multiplication ratio is variable, subject to several factors.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] Agricultural improvements can raise the ratio, and revisions were recommended in 2018 by the Indian Council of Agricultural Research.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] Alexander Mitscherlich studied crop yields in 1909 and articulated a "law of physiological relations".
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] Liebig's Law of the Minimum was the formulation of an idea that yield of a crop was determined primarily by the amounts of plant food that were present in minimum quantities.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] His idea was discussed later as the Limiting Factor by BLACKMAN and again by MITSCHERLICH as the Law of Physiological Relations.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] The latter was expressed as a logarithmic function between yield and the quantity of plant food constituents, which is virtually the Law of Diminishing Returns.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/crop-yield] The relation was reviewed by Hans Schneeberger in 2009.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Whereas the human eye sees color of visible light in mostly three bands (long wavelengths, perceived as red; medium wavelengths, perceived as green; and short wavelengths, perceived as blue), spectral imaging divides the spectrum into many more bands.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] This technique of dividing images into bands can be extended beyond the visible.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] In hyperspectral imaging, the recorded spectra have fine wavelength resolution and cover a wide range of wavelengths.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral imaging measures continuous spectral bands, as opposed to multiband imaging which measures spaced spectral bands.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Engineers build hyperspectral sensors and processing systems for applications in astronomy, agriculture, molecular biology, biomedical imaging, geosciences, physics, and surveillance.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral sensors look at objects using a vast portion of the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Certain objects leave unique "fingerprints" in the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Known as spectral signatures, these "fingerprints" enable identification of the materials that make up a scanned object.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] For example, a spectral signature for oil helps geologists find new oil fields.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Figuratively speaking, hyperspectral sensors collect information as a set of "images." Each image represents a narrow wavelength range of the electromagnetic spectrum, also known as a spectral band.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] These "images" are combined to form a three-dimensional (*x*, *y*, *λ*) hyperspectral data cube for processing and analysis, where *x* and *y* represent two spatial dimensions of the scene, and *λ* represents the spectral dimension (comprising a range of wavelengths).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Technically speaking, there are four ways for sensors to sample the hyperspectral cube: spatial scanning, spectral scanning, snapshot imaging, and spatio-spectral scanning.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral cubes are generated from airborne sensors like NASA's *Airborne Visible/Infrared Imaging Spectrometer* (AVIRIS), or from satellites like NASA's EO-1 with its hyperspectral instrument Hyperion.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] However, for many development and validation studies, handheld sensors are used.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] The precision of these sensors is typically measured in spectral resolution, which is the width of each band of the spectrum that is captured.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] If the scanner detects a large number of fairly narrow frequency bands, it is possible to identify objects even if they are only captured in a handful of pixels.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] However, spatial resolution is a factor in addition to spectral resolution.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] If the pixels are too large, then multiple objects are captured in the same pixel and become difficult to identify.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] If the pixels are too small, then the intensity captured by each sensor cell is low, and the decreased signal-to-noise ratio reduces the reliability of measured features.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] The acquisition and processing of hyperspectral images is also referred to as imaging spectroscopy or, with reference to the hyperspectral cube, as 3D spectroscopy.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] There are four basic techniques for acquiring the three-dimensional (*x*, *y*, *λ*) dataset of a hyperspectral cube.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] The choice of technique depends on the specific application, seeing that each technique has context-dependent advantages and disadvantages.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] In spatial scanning, each two-dimensional (2D) sensor output represents a full slit spectrum (*x*, *λ*).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral imaging (HSI) devices for spatial scanning obtain slit spectra by projecting a strip of the scene onto a slit and dispersing the slit image with a prism or a grating.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] These systems have the drawback of having the image analyzed per lines (with a push broom scanner) and also having some mechanical parts integrated into the optical train.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] With these *line-scan cameras*, the spatial dimension is collected through platform movement or scanning.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] This requires stabilized mounts or accurate pointing information to 'reconstruct' the image.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Nonetheless, line-scan systems are particularly common in remote sensing, where it is sensible to use mobile platforms.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Line-scan systems are also used to scan materials moving by on a conveyor belt.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] A special case of line scanning is *point scanning* (with a whisk broom scanner), where a point-like aperture is used instead of a slit, and the sensor is essentially one-dimensional instead of 2D.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] In spectral scanning, each 2D sensor output represents a monochromatic (i.e. single wavelength), spatial (*x*, *y*)-map of the scene.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] HSI devices for spectral scanning are typically based on optical band-pass filters (either tunable or fixed).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] The scene is spectrally scanned by exchanging one filter after another while the platform remains stationary.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] In such "staring", wavelength scanning systems, spectral smearing can occur if there is movement within the scene, invalidating spectral correlation/detection.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Nonetheless, there is the advantage of being able to pick and choose spectral bands, and having a direct representation of the two spatial dimensions of the scene.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] If the imaging system is used on a moving platform, such as an airplane, acquired images at different wavelengths corresponds to different areas of the scene.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] The spatial features on each of the images may be used to realign the pixels.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] In non-scanning, a single 2D sensor output contains all spatial (*x*, *y*) and spectral (*λ*) data.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] HSI devices for non-scanning yield the full datacube at once, without any scanning.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Figuratively speaking, a single snapshot represents a perspective projection of the datacube, from which its three-dimensional structure can be reconstructed.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] The most prominent benefits of these snapshot hyperspectral imaging systems are the *snapshot advantage* (higher light throughput) and shorter acquisition time.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] However, computational effort and manufacturing costs are high.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] In an effort to reduce the computational demands and potentially the high cost of non-scanning hyperspectral instrumentation, prototype devices based on Multivariate Optical Computing have been demonstrated.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] These devices have been based on the Multivariate Optical Element spectral calculation engine or the Spatial Light Modulator spectral calculation engine.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] In these platforms, chemical information is calculated in the optical domain prior to imaging such that the chemical image relies on conventional camera systems with no further computing.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] As a disadvantage of these systems, no spectral information is ever acquired, i.e. only the chemical information, such that post processing or reanalysis is not possible.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] In spatiospectral scanning, each 2D sensor output represents a wavelength-coded ("rainbow-colored", *λ* = *λ*(*y*)), spatial (*x*, *y*)-map of the scene.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] A prototype for this technique, introduced in 2014, consists of a camera at some *non-zero* distance behind a basic slit spectroscope (slit + dispersive element).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Advanced spatiospectral scanning systems can be obtained by placing a dispersive element before a spatial scanning system.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Scanning can be achieved by moving the whole system relative to the scene, by moving the camera alone, or by moving the slit alone.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Spatiospectral scanning unites some advantages of spatial and spectral scanning, thereby alleviating some of their disadvantages.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral imaging is part of a class of techniques commonly referred to as spectral imaging or spectral analysis.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] The term "hyperspectral imaging" derives from the development of NASA's Airborne Imaging Spectrometer (AIS) and AVIRIS in the mid-1980s.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Although NASA prefers the earlier term "imaging spectroscopy" over "hyperspectral imaging," use of the latter term has become more prevalent in scientific and non-scientific language.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] In a peer reviewed letter, experts recommend using the terms "imaging spectroscopy" or "spectral imaging" and avoiding exaggerated prefixes such as "hyper-," "super-" and "ultra-," to prevent misnomers in discussion.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral imaging is related to multispectral imaging.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] The distinction between hyper- and multi-band is sometimes based incorrectly on an arbitrary "number of bands" or on the type of measurement.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral imaging (HSI) uses continuous and contiguous ranges of wavelengths (e.g.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] 400 - 1100 nm in steps of 1 nm) whilst multiband imaging (MSI) uses a subset of targeted wavelengths at chosen locations (e.g.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Multiband imaging deals with several images at discrete and somewhat narrow bands.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Being "discrete and somewhat narrow" is what distinguishes multispectral imaging in the visible wavelength from color photography.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] A multispectral sensor may have many bands covering the spectrum from the visible to the longwave infrared.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Multispectral images do not produce the "spectrum" of an object.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Landsat is a prominent practical example of multispectral imaging.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral deals with imaging narrow spectral bands over a continuous spectral range, producing the spectra of all pixels in the scene.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] A sensor with only 20 bands can also be hyperspectral when it covers the range from 500 to 700 nm with 20 bands each 10 nm wide, while a sensor with 20 discrete bands covering the visible, near, short wave, medium wave and long wave infrared would be considered multispectral.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] In addition, some formal standards define HSI using a minimum number of spectral channels.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] For example, the IEEE 4001 standard for hyperspectral data characterization defines hyperspectral imagery as containing 30 or more spectral bands, primarily for data interoperability, system classification, and metadata standardization.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral remote sensing is used in a wide array of applications.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] This technology is continually becoming more available to the public.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Organizations such as NASA and the USGS have catalogues of various minerals and their spectral signatures, and have posted them online to make them readily available for researchers.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] On a smaller scale, NIR hyperspectral imaging can be used to rapidly monitor the application of pesticides to individual seeds for quality control of the optimum dose and homogeneous coverage.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Although the cost of acquiring hyperspectral images is typically high for specific crops and in specific climates, hyperspectral remote sensing use is increasing for monitoring the development and health of crops.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] In Australia, work is under way to use imaging spectrometers to detect grape variety and develop an early warning system for disease outbreaks.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Furthermore, work is under way to use hyperspectral data to detect the chemical composition of plants, which can be used to detect the nutrient and water status of wheat in irrigated systems.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Another application in agriculture is the detection of animal proteins in compound feeds to avoid bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE), also known as mad-cow disease.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Different studies have been done to propose alternative tools to the reference method of detection, (classical microscopy).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] One of the first alternatives is near infrared microscopy (NIR), which combines the advantages of microscopy and NIR.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] In 2004, the first study relating this problem with hyperspectral imaging was published.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral libraries that are representative of the diversity of ingredients usually present in the preparation of compound feeds were constructed.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] These libraries can be used together with chemometric tools to investigate the limit of detection, specificity and reproducibility of the NIR hyperspectral imaging method for the detection and quantification of animal ingredients in feed.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] HSI cameras can also be used to detect stress from heavy metals in plants and become an earlier and faster alternative to post-harvest wet chemical methods.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral imaging is also used in zoology; it is used to investigate the spatial distribution of coloration and its extension into the near-infrared and SWIR range of the spectrum.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Some animals for example, such as some tropical frogs and certain leaf-sitting insects are highly reflective in the near-infrared.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral imaging can provide information about the chemical constituents of materials which makes it useful for waste sorting and recycling.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] It has been applied to distinguish between substances with different fabrics and to identify natural, animal and synthetic fibers.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] HSI cameras can be integrated with machine vision systems and, via simplifying platforms, allow end-customers to create new waste sorting applications and other sorting/identification applications.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] A system of machine learning and hyperspectral camera can distinguish between 12 different types of plastics such as PET and PP for automated separation of waste of, as of 2020, highly unstandardized plastics products and packaging.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Researchers at the Université de Montréal are working with Photon etc. and Optina Diagnostics to test the use of hyperspectral photography in the diagnosis of retinopathy and macular edema before damage to the eye occurs.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] The metabolic hyperspectral camera will detect a drop in oxygen consumption in the retina, which indicates potential disease.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] An ophthalmologist will then be able to treat the retina with injections to prevent any potential damage.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] In the food processing industry, hyperspectral imaging, combined with intelligent software, enables digital sorters (also called optical sorters) to identify and remove defects and foreign material (FM) that are invisible to traditional camera and laser sorters.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] By improving the accuracy of defect and FM removal, the food processor's objective is to enhance product quality and increase yields.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Adopting hyperspectral imaging on digital sorters achieves non-destructive, 100 percent inspection in-line at full production volumes.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] The sorter's software compares the hyperspectral images collected to user-defined accept/reject thresholds, and the ejection system automatically removes defects and foreign material.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Here, improved product quality, low false reject rates and the ability to handle high incoming defect loads often justify the cost of the technology.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Commercial adoption of hyperspectral sorters is also advancing at a fast pace in the potato processing industry where the technology promises to solve a number of outstanding product quality problems.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Work is under way to use hyperspectral imaging to detect "sugar ends," "hollow heart" and "common scab," conditions that plague potato processors.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Geological samples, such as drill cores, can be rapidly mapped for nearly all minerals of commercial interest with hyperspectral imaging.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Fusion of SWIR and LWIR spectral imaging is standard for the detection of minerals in the feldspar, silica, calcite, garnet, and olivine groups, as these minerals have their most distinctive and strongest spectral signature in the LWIR regions.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral remote sensing of minerals is well developed.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Many minerals can be identified from airborne images, and their relation to the presence of valuable minerals, such as gold and diamonds, is well understood.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Currently, progress is towards understanding the relationship between oil and gas leakages from pipelines and natural wells, and their effects on the vegetation and the spectral signatures.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Recent work includes the PhD dissertations of Werff and Noomen.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral surveillance is the implementation of hyperspectral scanning technology for surveillance purposes.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral imaging is particularly useful in military surveillance because of countermeasures that military entities now take to avoid airborne surveillance.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] The idea that drives hyperspectral surveillance is that hyperspectral scanning draws information from such a large portion of the light spectrum that any given object should have a unique spectral signature in at least a few of the many bands that are scanned.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral imaging has also shown potential to be used in facial recognition purposes.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Facial recognition algorithms using hyperspectral imaging have been shown to perform better than algorithms using traditional imaging.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Traditionally, commercially available thermal infrared hyperspectral imaging systems have needed liquid nitrogen or helium cooling, which has made them impractical for most surveillance applications.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] In 2010, Specim introduced a thermal infrared hyperspectral camera that can be used for outdoor surveillance and UAV applications without an external light source such as the sun or the moon.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] In astronomy, hyperspectral imaging is used to determine a spatially resolved spectral image.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Since a spectrum is an important diagnostic, having a spectrum for each pixel allows more science cases to be addressed.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] In astronomy, this technique is commonly referred to as integral field spectroscopy, and examples of this technique include FLAMES and SINFONI on the Very Large Telescope.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] The Advanced CCD Imaging Spectrometer on the Chandra X-ray Observatory uses this technique.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Soldiers can be exposed to a wide variety of chemical hazards.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] These threats are mostly invisible but detectable by hyperspectral imaging technology.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] The Telops Hyper-Cam, introduced in 2005, has demonstrated this at distances up to 5 km.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral imaging in the visible near-infrared (VNIR) spectral range can effectively distinguish between dye-based and pigment-based inkjet prints, despite their similar appearance to the naked eye.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Research has demonstrated that these two ink types exhibit significantly different spectral characteristics, particularly in the near-infrared band (800-1000 nm), where dye-based inks show substantially higher reflectance compared to pigment-based inks.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] This difference is especially pronounced for black ink, where pigment-based ink maintains low reflectance across the entire VNIR spectrum while dye-based ink reflectance increases dramatically in the NIR range.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Thus, hyperspectral technology may offer practical applications in detecting print forgery, validating archival-quality prints, and potentially identifying specific printer types used to create documents.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Most countries require continuous monitoring of emissions produced by coal and oil-fired power plants, municipal and hazardous waste incinerators, cement plants, as well as many other types of industrial sources.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] This monitoring is usually performed using extractive sampling systems coupled with infrared spectroscopy techniques.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Some recent standoff measurements performed allowed the evaluation of the air quality but not many remote independent methods allow for low uncertainty measurements.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Recent research indicates that hyperspectral imaging may be useful to detect the development of cracks in pavements which are hard to detect from images taken with visible spectrum cameras.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral imaging has also been used to detect cancer, identify nerves and analyze bruises.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral imaging has recently been explored for use in autonomous driving and advanced driver-assistance systems.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] It can be used to improve pedestrian separability and object classification compared with conventional RGB cameras, and to help distinguish road conditions such as water or snow on the surface.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] The primary advantage to hyperspectral imaging is that, because an entire spectrum is acquired at each point, the operator needs no prior knowledge of the sample, and postprocessing allows all available information from the dataset to be mined.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Hyperspectral imaging can also take advantage of the spatial relationships among the different spectra in a neighbourhood, allowing more elaborate spectral-spatial models for a more accurate segmentation and classification of the image.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] The high cost and complexity of hyperspectral imaging equipment has limited its adoption, and analysis of hyperspectral data requires high computing power, especially for real-time or mobile applications.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Significant data storage and transmission capacities are necessary, since hyperspectral cubes are large, multidimensional datasets—for example, NASA's AVIRIS sensor, in use since 1987, produces about 500 megabytes per datacube.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Significant research has gone into onboard processing of hyperspectral data in satellites, to reduce transmission sizes by only sending detection results.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/hyperspectral-imaging] Increasingly, deep learning is being researched to lower the computational cost of processing hyperspectral data.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] The definition “half the total leaf area” pertains to biological processes, such as gas exchange, whereas the definition “projected leaf area” is rarely used, because the projection of a given area in one direction may differ in another direction when leaves are not flat, thick, or 3D-shaped.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] Moreover, “ground surface area” is specifically defined as “horizontal ground surface area” to clarify LAI on a sloping surface.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] The definition “half the total leaf area per unit horizontal ground surface area” is suitable for all kinds of leaves and flat or sloping surfaces.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] LAI is commonly used as an indicator of the growth rate of a plant.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] LAI is a complex variable that relates not only to the size of the canopy, but also to its density, and the angle at which leaves are oriented in relation to one another and to light sources.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] In addition, LAI varies with seasonal changes in plant activity, and is typically highest in the spring when new leaves are being produced and lowest in late summer or early fall when leaves senesce (and may be shed).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] LAI is a measure for the total area of leaves per unit ground area and directly related to the amount of light that can be intercepted by plants.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] It is an important variable used to predict photosynthetic primary production, evapotranspiration and as a reference tool for crop growth.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] As such, LAI plays an essential role in theoretical production ecology.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] where *P*max designates the maximum primary production and c designates a crop-specific growth coefficient.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] This inverse exponential function is called the **primary production function**.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] LAI ranges from 0 (bare ground) to over 10 (dense conifer forests).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] LAI can be determined directly by taking a statistically significant sample of foliage from a plant canopy, measuring the leaf area per sample plot and dividing it by the plot land surface area.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] Indirect methods measure canopy geometry or light extinction and relate it to LAI.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] Direct methods can be easily applied on deciduous species by collecting leaves during leaf fall in traps of certain area distributed below the canopy.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] The area of the collected leaves can be measured using a leaf area meter or an image scanner and image analysis software (ImageJ) and mobile applications (Leafscan, Petiole Pro, Easy Leaf Area).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] The measured leaf area can then be divided by the area of the traps to obtain LAI.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] Alternatively, leaf area can be measured on a sub-sample of the collected leaves and linked to the leaf dry mass (e.g. via Specific Leaf Area, SLA cm2/g).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] That way it is not necessary to measure the area of all leaves one by one, but weigh the collected leaves after drying (at 60–80 °C for 48 h).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] Leaf dry mass multiplied by the specific leaf area is converted into leaf area.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] Direct methods in evergreen species are necessarily destructive.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] However, they are widely used in crops and pastures by harvesting the vegetation and measuring leaf area within a certain ground surface area.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] It is very difficult (and also unethical) to apply such destructive techniques in natural ecosystems, particularly in forests of evergreen tree species.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] Foresters have developed techniques that determine leaf area in evergreen forests through allometric relationships.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] Due to the difficulties and the limitations of the direct methods for estimating LAI, they are mostly used as reference for indirect methods that are easier and faster to apply.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] Due to the subjectivity and labor involved with the first method, indirect non-contact measurements are typically preferred.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] Hemispherical photography methods estimate LAI and other canopy structure attributes from analyzing upward-looking fisheye photographs taken beneath the plant canopy.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] The LAI-2200 calculates LAI and other canopy structure attributes from solar radiation measurements made with a wide-angle optical sensor.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] Measurements made above and below the canopy are used to determine canopy light interception at five angles, from which LAI is computed using a model of radiative transfer in vegetative canopies based on Beer's law .
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] The LP-80 calculates LAI by means of measuring the difference between light levels above the canopy and at ground level, and factoring in the leaf angle distribution, solar zenith angle, and plant extinction coefficient.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] Such indirect methods, where LAI is calculated based upon observations of other variables (canopy geometry, light interception, leaf length and width, etc.) are generally faster, amenable to automation, and thereby allow for a larger number of spatial samples to be obtained.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] For reasons of convenience when compared to the direct (destructive) methods, these tools are becoming more and more important.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] The disadvantage of the direct method is that it is destructive, time consuming and expensive, especially if the study area is very large.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] The disadvantage of the indirect method is that in some cases it can underestimate the value of LAI in very dense canopies, as it does not account for leaves that lie on each other, and essentially act as one leaf according to the theoretical LAI models.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] Ignorance of non-randomness within canopies may cause underestimation of LAI up to 25%, introducing path length distribution in the indirect method can improve the measuring accuracy of LAI.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/leaf-area-index] Indirect estimation of LAI is also sensitive to the data analysis methods of choices.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Multispectral imaging measures light in a small number (typically 3 to 15) of spectral bands.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] *Hyperspectral imaging* is a special case of spectral imaging where often hundreds of contiguous spectral bands are available.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] For different purposes, different combinations of spectral bands can be used.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] They are usually represented with red, green, and blue channels.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Mapping of bands to colors depends on the purpose of the image and the personal preferences of the analysts.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Thermal infrared is often omitted from consideration due to poor spatial resolution, except for special purposes.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] NIR is often shown as red, causing vegetation-covered areas to appear red.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Unlike other aerial photographic and satellite image interpretation work, these multispectral images do not make it easy to identify directly the feature type by visual inspection.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Hence the remote sensing data has to be classified first, followed by processing by various data enhancement techniques so as to help the user to understand the features that are present in the image.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Such classification is a complex task which involves rigorous validation of the training samples depending on the classification algorithm used.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] The techniques can be grouped mainly into two types.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Supervised classification makes use of training samples.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Training samples are areas on the ground for which there is ground truth, that is, what is there is known.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] The spectral signatures of the training areas are used to search for similar signatures in the remaining pixels of the image, and we will classify accordingly.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] This use of training samples for classification is called supervised classification.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Expert knowledge is very important in this method since the selection of the training samples and a biased selection can badly affect the accuracy of classification.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Popular techniques include the maximum likelihood principle and convolutional neural network.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] The maximum likelihood principle calculates the probability of a pixel belonging to a class (i.e. feature) and allots the pixel to its most probable class.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Newer convolutional neural network based methods account for both spatial proximity and entire spectra to determine the most likely class.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] In case of unsupervised classification no prior knowledge is required for classifying the features of the image.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] The natural clustering or grouping of the pixel values (i.e. the gray levels of the pixels) are observed.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Then a threshold is defined for adopting the number of classes in the image.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] The finer the threshold value, the more classes there will be.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] However, beyond a certain limit the same class will be represented in different classes in the sense that variation in the class is represented.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] After forming the clusters, ground truth validation is done to identify the class the image pixel belongs to.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Thus in this unsupervised classification a priori information about the classes is not required.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] One of the popular methods in unsupervised classification is k-means clustering.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Multispectral imaging measures light emission and is often used in detecting or tracking military targets.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] In 2003, researchers at the United States Army Research Laboratory and the Federal Laboratory Collaborative Technology Alliance reported a dual band multispectral imaging focal plane array (FPA).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] This FPA allowed researchers to look at two infrared (IR) planes at the same time.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Because mid-wave infrared (MWIR) and long wave infrared (LWIR) technologies measure radiation inherent to the object and require no external light source, they also are referred to as thermal imaging methods.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] The brightness of the image produced by a thermal imager depends on the objects emissivity and temperature.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Every material has an infrared signature that aids in the identification of the object.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] These signatures are less pronounced in hyperspectral systems (which image in many more bands than multispectral systems) and when exposed to wind and, more dramatically, to rain.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Sometimes the surface of the target may reflect infrared energy.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] This reflection may misconstrue the true reading of the objects' inherent radiation.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Imaging systems that use MWIR technology function better with solar reflections on the target's surface and produce more definitive images of hot objects, such as engines, compared to LWIR technology.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] However, LWIR operates better in hazy environments like smoke or fog because less scattering occurs in the longer wavelengths.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Researchers claim that dual-band technologies combine these advantages to provide more information from an image, particularly in the realm of target tracking.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] For nighttime target detection, thermal imaging outperformed single-band multispectral imaging.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Dual band MWIR and LWIR technology resulted in better visualization during the nighttime than MWIR alone.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] The US Army reports that its dual band LWIR/MWIR FPA demonstrated better visualizing of tactical vehicles than MWIR alone after tracking them through both day and night.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] By analyzing the emissivity of ground surfaces, multispectral imaging can detect the presence of underground missiles.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Surface and sub-surface soil possess different physical and chemical properties that appear in spectral analysis.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Disturbed soil has increased emissivity in the wavelength range of 8.5 to 9.5 micrometers while demonstrating no change in wavelengths greater than 10 micrometers.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] The US Army Research Laboratory's dual MWIR/LWIR FPA used "red" and "blue" detectors to search for areas with enhanced emissivity.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] The red detector acts as a backdrop, verifying realms of undisturbed soil areas, as it is sensitive to the 10.4 micrometer wavelength.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] The blue detector is sensitive to wavelengths of 9.3 micrometers.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] If the intensity of the blue image changes when scanning, that region is likely disturbed*.* The scientists reported that fusing these two images increased detection capabilities.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Intercepting an intercontinental ballistic missile (ICBM) in its boost phase requires imaging of the hard body as well as the rocket plumes.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] MWIR presents a strong signal from highly heated objects including rocket plumes, while LWIR produces emissions from the missile's body material.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] The US Army Research Laboratory reported that with their dual-band MWIR/LWIR technology, tracking of the Atlas 5 Evolved Expendable Launch Vehicles, similar in design to ICBMs, picked up both the missile body and plumage.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Most radiometers for remote sensing (RS) acquire multispectral images.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Dividing the spectrum into many bands, multispectral is the opposite of panchromatic, which records only the total intensity of radiation falling on each pixel.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Usually, Earth observation satellites have three or more radiometers.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Each acquires one digital image (in remote sensing, called a 'scene') in a small spectral band.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] The bands are grouped into wavelength regions based on the origin of the light and the interests of the researchers.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Modern weather satellites produce imagery in a variety of spectra.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] In the case of Landsat satellites, several different band designations have been used, with as many as 11 bands (Landsat 8) comprising a multispectral image.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Spectral imaging with a higher radiometric resolution (involving hundreds or thousands of bands), finer spectral resolution (involving smaller bands), or wider spectral coverage may be called hyperspectral or ultraspectral.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Multispectral imaging can be employed for investigation of paintings and other works of art.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] The painting is irradiated by ultraviolet, visible and infrared rays and the reflected radiation is recorded in a camera sensitive in this region of the spectrum.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] The image can also be registered using the transmitted instead of reflected radiation.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] In special cases the painting can be irradiated by UV, VIS or IR rays and the fluorescence of pigments or varnishes can be registered.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Multispectral analysis has assisted in the interpretation of ancient papyri, such as those found at Herculaneum, by imaging the fragments in the infrared range (1000 nm).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Often, the text on the documents appears to the naked eye as black ink on black paper.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] At 1000 nm, the difference in how paper and ink reflect infrared light makes the text clearly readable.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] It has also been used to image the Archimedes palimpsest by imaging the parchment leaves in bandwidths from 365–870 nm, and then using advanced digital image processing techniques to reveal the undertext with Archimedes' work.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Multispectral imaging has been used in a Mellon Foundation project at Yale University to compare inks in medieval English manuscripts.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Multispectral imaging has also been used to examine discolorations and stains on old books and manuscripts.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Comparing the "spectral fingerprint" of a stain to the characteristics of known chemical substances can make it possible to identify the stain.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] This technique has been used to examine medical and alchemical texts, seeking hints about the activities of early chemists and the possible chemical substances they may have used in their experiments.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/multispectral-imaging] Like a cook spilling flour or vinegar on a cookbook, an early chemist might have left tangible evidence on the pages of the ingredients used to make medicines.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The **normalized difference vegetation index** (**NDVI**) is a widely used metric for quantifying the health and density of vegetation using sensor data.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] It is calculated from spectrometric data at two specific bands: red and near-infrared.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The spectrometric data is usually sourced from remote sensors, such as satellites.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The metric is popular in industry because of its accuracy.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] It has a high correlation with the true state of vegetation on the ground.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The index is easy to interpret: NDVI will be a value between -1 and 1, where values close to zero will indicate little to no vegetation, negative values are associated with non-land surfaces or water, and higher values correspond to healthy, dense vegetation.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] It is used in applications such as agriculture, drought monitoring, and ecosystem analysis.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The exploration of outer space started in earnest with the launch of Sputnik 1 by the Soviet Union on 4 October 1957.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] This was the first man-made satellite orbiting the Earth.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Subsequent successful launches, both in the Soviet Union (e.g., the Sputnik and Cosmos programs), and in the U.S.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] (e.g., the Explorer program), quickly led to the design and operation of dedicated meteorological satellites.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] These are orbiting platforms embarking instruments specially designed to observe the Earth's atmosphere and surface with a view to improve weather forecasting.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Starting in 1960, the TIROS series of satellites embarked television cameras and radiometers.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] This was later (1964 onwards) followed by the Nimbus satellites and the family of Advanced Very High Resolution Radiometer instruments on board the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) platforms.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The latter measures the reflectance of the planet in red and near-infrared bands, as well as in the thermal infrared.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] In parallel, NASA developed the Earth Resources Technology Satellite (ERTS), which became the precursor to the Landsat program.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] These early sensors had minimal spectral resolution, but tended to include bands in the red and near-infrared, which are useful to distinguish vegetation and clouds, amongst other targets.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] With the launch of the first ERTS satellite – which was soon to be renamed Landsat 1 – on July 23, 1972 with its MultiSpectral Scanner (MSS) NASA funded a number of investigations to determine its capabilities for Earth remote sensing.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] One of those early studies was directed toward examining the spring vegetation green-up and subsequent summer and fall dry-down (the so-called "vernal advancement and retrogradation") throughout the north to south expanse of the Great Plains region of the central U.S.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] This region covered a wide range of latitudes from the southern tip of Texas to the U.S.-Canada border, which resulted in a wide range of solar zenith angles at the time of the satellite observations.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The researchers for this Great Plains study (PhD student Donald Deering and his advisor Dr.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Robert Hass) found that their ability to correlate, or quantify, the biophysical characteristics of the rangeland vegetation of this region from the satellite spectral signals was confounded by these differences in solar zenith angle across this strong latitudinal gradient.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] With the assistance of a resident mathematician (Dr.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] John Schell), they studied solutions to this dilemma and subsequently developed the ratio of the difference of the red and infrared radiances over their sum as a means to adjust for or "normalize" the effects of the solar zenith angle.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The earliest reported use of NDVI in the Great Plains study was in 1973 by Rouse et al.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] John Rouse was the Director of the Remote Sensing Center of Texas A&M University where the Great Plains study was conducted).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] However, they were preceded in formulating a normalized difference spectral index by Kriegler et al. in 1969.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Soon after the launch of ERTS-1 (Landsat-1), Compton Tucker of NASA's Goddard Space Flight Center produced a series of early scientific journal articles describing uses of the NDVI.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Thus, NDVI was one of the most successful of many attempts to simply and quickly identify vegetated areas and their "condition," and it remains the most well-known and used index to detect live green plant canopies in multispectral remote sensing data.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Once the feasibility to detect vegetation had been demonstrated, users tended to also use the NDVI to quantify the photosynthetic capacity of plant canopies.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] This, however, can be a rather more complex undertaking if not done properly, as is discussed below.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Live green plants absorb solar radiation in the photosynthetically active radiation (PAR) spectral region, which they use as a source of energy in the process of photosynthesis.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Leaf cells have also evolved to re-emit solar radiation in the near-infrared spectral region (which carries approximately half of the total incoming solar energy), because the photon energy at wavelengths longer than about 700 nanometers is too low to synthesize organic molecules.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] A strong absorption at these wavelengths would only result in overheating the plant and possibly damaging the tissues.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Hence, live green plants appear relatively dark in the PAR and relatively bright in the near-infrared.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] By contrast, clouds and snow tend to be rather bright in the red (as well as other visible wavelengths) and quite dark in the near-infrared.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The pigment in plant leaves, chlorophyll, strongly absorbs visible light (from 400 to 700 nm) for use in photosynthesis.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The cell structure of the leaves, on the other hand, strongly reflects near-infrared light (from 700 to 1100 nm).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The more leaves a plant has, the more these wavelengths of light are affected.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Since early instruments of Earth Observation, such as NASA's ERTS and NOAA's AVHRR, acquired data in visible and near-infrared, it was natural to exploit the strong differences in plant reflectance to determine their spatial distribution in these satellite images.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] where Red and NIR stand for the spectral reflectance measurements acquired in the red (visible) and near-infrared regions, respectively.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] These spectral reflectances are themselves ratios of the reflected radiation to the incoming radiation in each spectral band individually, hence they take on values between 0 and 1.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] By design, the NDVI itself thus varies between -1 and +1.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] NDVI is functionally, but not linearly, equivalent to the simple infrared/red ratio (NIR/VIS).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The advantage of NDVI over a simple infrared/red ratio is therefore generally limited to any possible linearity of its functional relationship with vegetation properties (e.g. biomass).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The simple ratio (unlike NDVI) is always positive, which may have practical advantages, but it also has a mathematically infinite range (0 to infinity), which can be a practical disadvantage as compared to NDVI.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Also in this regard, note that the VIS term in the numerator of NDVI only scales the result, thereby creating negative values.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] NDVI is functionally *and linearly* equivalent to the ratio NIR / (NIR+VIS), which ranges from 0 to 1 and is thus never negative nor limitless in range.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] But the most important concept in the understanding of the NDVI algebraic formula is that, despite its name, it is a transformation of a spectral ratio (NIR/VIS), and it has no functional relationship to a spectral difference (NIR-VIS).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] In general, if there is much more reflected radiation in near-infrared wavelengths than in visible wavelengths, then the vegetation in that pixel is likely to be dense and may contain some type of forest.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Subsequent work has shown that the NDVI is directly related to the photosynthetic capacity and hence energy absorption of plant canopies.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Although the index can take negative values, even in densely populated urban areas the NDVI usually has a (small) positive value.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Negative values are more likely to be observed in the atmosphere and some specific materials.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Within precision agriculture, NDVI data is used to assess crop health.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Today, this often involves agricultural drones, which are paired with NDVI to compare data and recognize crop health issues.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] One example of this is agriculture drones from PrecisionHawk and Sentera, which allow agriculturalists to capture and process NDVI data within one day, a change from the traditional NDVI uses and their long lag times.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] In addition to drones, NDVI is used to monitor crop growth in stages over time, from early growth to maturity, helping to track how vegetation sprouts through its growing season.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] This data collection helps detect spatial variability within field to check if some areas are growing healthier than others and if their timing is accurate for what stage they should be in.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] More specifically, farmers use NDVI to track things such as irrigation levels, application of fertilizer, and help reduce their waste and cost.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] It can estimate leaf area index (LAI), biomass, vegetation cover, which farmers also need to determine crop yield.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] This includes being able to identify plant stress much sooner than it can be seen.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] This could include water stress, nutrient deficiencies, or diseases.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Since there is a prediction aspect to NDVI, it has been able to be used in yield prediction models since higher NDVI is more often linked to greater productivity/biomass.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Using a time-series, NDVI data gives farmers the opportunity to keep track of seasonal trends, compare those to that of previous years and brace for changes in upcoming climate variability that includes more drought or heatwaves.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] For example, NDVI can be used to monitor drought by tracking changes in vegetation green over time, where lower values can indicate plant stress due to reduced water availability.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] This helps in analyzing large-scale ecosystem changes which includes seasonal vegetation cycles and long-term changes caused by climate change and land use change.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] It also has applications in detecting deforestation and land cover damage since decreases in values often point to vegetation loss or degradation.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] This data is applied in urban studies to examine the relationship between surface temperature and vegetation cover, more useful in research on urban heat islands.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] It can be seen from its mathematical definition that the NDVI of an area containing a dense vegetation canopy will tend to positive values (say 0.3 to 0.8) while clouds and snow fields will be characterized by negative values of this index.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The NDVI has been widely used in applications for which it was not originally designed.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Using the NDVI for quantitative assessments (as opposed to qualitative surveys as indicated above) raises a number of issues that may seriously limit the actual usefulness of this index if they are not properly addressed.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] The following subsections review some of these issues.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] NDVI is a very widely using system, however, it can become hard to interpret due to an oversimplification of more complex surface signals.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Satellite data that is used includes a mixture of vegetation, soil, shadows, and the atmosphere itself, so it does not simply represent vegetation.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Due to this oversimplification, information can be lost and in fact be misinterpreted of any actual vegetation conditions occurring at the time.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Additionally, even if NDVI can cover larger areas, it's hard for it to capture individual plants which causes mismatches in field and satellite data.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] This makes linking productivity to an area much more uncertain for people like farmers.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Differences between sensors and data processing methods can produce slightly different NDVI values making it hard for people to compare datasets from different timescales or platforms.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] This can also happen with the way people configure their sensor calibration or just how the resolution taken at the time was processed that could produce these changes.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] With this in mind, because of these limitation, NDVI can only be more reliably used for general vegetation pattern alongside other indices to provide a more accurate analysis and interpretation.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] A number of derivatives and alternatives to NDVI have been proposed in the scientific literature to address these limitations, including the Perpendicular Vegetation Index, the soil-adjusted vegetation index, the atmospherically resistant vegetation index and the global environment monitoring index.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] Each of these attempted to include intrinsic correction(s) for one or more perturbing factors.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] A current alternative adopted by USGS is the enhanced vegetation index (EVI), correcting for soil effects, canopy background, and aerosol influences.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/normalized-difference-vegetation-index] In spite of many possible perturbing factors upon the NDVI, it remains a valuable quantitative vegetation monitoring tool when the photosynthetic capacity of the land surface needs to be studied at the appropriate spatial scale for various phenomena.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] In current usage, the term *remote sensing* generally refers to the use of satellite- or airborne-based sensor technologies to detect and classify objects on Earth.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] It includes the surface and the atmosphere and oceans, based on propagated signals (e.g. electromagnetic radiation).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] It may be split into "active" remote sensing (when a signal is emitted by a sensor mounted on a satellite or aircraft to the object and its reflection is detected by the sensor) and "passive" remote sensing (when the reflection of sunlight is detected by the sensor).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Remote sensing can be divided into two types of methods: *Passive remote sensing* and *active remote sensing.* Passive sensors gather radiation that is emitted or reflected by the object or surrounding areas.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Reflected sunlight is the most common source of radiation measured by passive sensors.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Examples of passive remote sensors include film photography, infrared, charge-coupled devices, and radiometers.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Active collection, on the other hand, emits energy in order to scan objects and areas whereupon a sensor then detects and measures the radiation that is reflected or backscattered from the target.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Radar and lidar are examples of active remote sensing where the time delay between emission and return is measured, establishing the location, speed and direction of an object.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Remote sensing makes it possible to collect data of dangerous or inaccessible areas.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Remote sensing applications include monitoring deforestation in areas such as the Amazon Basin, glacial features in Arctic and Antarctic regions, and depth sounding of coastal and ocean depths.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Military collection during the Cold War made use of stand-off collection of data about dangerous border areas.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Remote sensing also replaces costly and slow data collection on the ground, ensuring in the process that areas or objects are not disturbed.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The basis for multispectral collection and analysis is that of examined areas or objects that reflect or emit radiation that stand out from surrounding areas.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] For a summary of major remote sensing satellite systems see the overview table.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Conventional radar is mostly associated with air traffic control, early warning, and certain large-scale meteorological data.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Doppler radar is used by local law enforcements' monitoring of speed limits and in enhanced meteorological collection such as wind speed and direction within weather systems in addition to precipitation location and intensity.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Other types of active collection includes plasmas in the ionosphere.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Interferometric synthetic aperture radar is used to produce precise digital elevation models of large scale terrain (See RADARSAT, TerraSAR-X, Magellan).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Laser and radar altimeters on satellites have provided a wide range of data.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] By measuring the bulges of water caused by gravity, they map features on the seafloor to a resolution of a mile or so.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] By measuring the height and wavelength of ocean waves, the altimeters measure wind speeds and direction, and surface ocean currents and directions.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Ultrasound (acoustic) and radar tide gauges are used to measure sea level, tides and wave direction in coastal and offshore tide gauges.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] LiDAR can be used to detect ground surface changes typically by creating Digital Surface Models (DSMs) or Digital Elevation Models (DEMs).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Vegetation remote sensing is a principal application of LIDAR.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The most common instruments in use are radiometers and photometers, which collect reflected and emitted radiation in a wide range of frequencies.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The most prevalent of these frequencies are visible and infrared sensors, followed by microwave, gamma-ray, and rarely, ultraviolet.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] They may also be used to detect the emission spectra of various chemicals, providing data on chemical concentrations in the atmosphere.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Radiometers are also used at night, as artificial light emissions are a key signature of human activity.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Applications include remote sensing of population, GDP, and damage to infrastructure from war or disasters.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Radiometers and radar onboard of satellites can be also used to monitor volcanic eruptions.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Spectropolarimetric Imaging has been reported to be useful for target tracking purposes by researchers at the U.S.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] They determined that manmade items possess polarimetric signatures that are not found in natural objects.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] These conclusions were drawn from the imaging of military trucks, like the Humvee, and trailers with their acousto-optic tunable filter dual hyperspectral and spectropolarimetric VNIR Spectropolarimetric Imager.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Stereographic pairs of aerial photographs have often been used to make topographic maps by imagery and terrain analysts in trafficability and highway departments for potential routes, in addition to modelling terrestrial habitat features.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Simultaneous multi-spectral platforms such as Landsat have been in use since the early 1970s.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] These thematic mappers take images in multiple wavelengths and are usually found on Earth observation satellites, including (for example) the Landsat program or the IKONOS satellite.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Maps of land cover and land use from thematic mapping can be used to prospect for minerals, detect or monitor land usage, detect invasive vegetation, deforestation, and examine the health of indigenous plants and crops (satellite crop monitoring), including entire farming regions or forests.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Prominent scientists using remote sensing for this purpose include Janet Franklin and Ruth DeFries.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Landsat images are used by regulatory agencies such as KYDOW to indicate water quality parameters including Secchi depth, chlorophyll density, and total phosphorus content.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Weather satellites are used in meteorology and climatology.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Hyperspectral imaging produces image cubes where each pixel has full spectral information with imaging narrow spectral bands over a contiguous spectral range.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Hyperspectral imagers are used in various applications including mineralogy, biology, defence, and environmental measurements.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Within the scope of the combat against desertification, remote sensing allows researchers to follow up and monitor risk areas in the long term, to determine desertification factors, to support decision-makers in defining relevant measures of environmental management, and to assess their impacts.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Remotely sensed multi- and hyperspectral images can be used for assessing biodiversity at different spatial scales.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Since the spectral properties of different plants species are unique, it is possible to get information about properties that relates to biodiversity such as habitat heterogeneity, spectral diversity and plant functional trait.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Remote sensing has also been used to detect rare plants to aid in conservation efforts.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Prediction, detection, and the ability to record biophysical conditions were possible from medium to very high resolutions.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Geodetic remote sensing can be gravimetric or geometric.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Overhead gravity data collection was first used in aerial submarine detection.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] This data revealed minute perturbations in the Earth's gravitational field that may be used to determine changes in the mass distribution of the Earth, which in turn may be used for geophysical studies, as in GRACE.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Geometric remote sensing includes position and deformation imaging using InSAR, LIDAR, etc.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Seismograms taken at different locations can locate and measure earthquakes (after they occur) by comparing the relative intensity and precise timings.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Ultrasound acoustic sensing is made up of ultrasound sensors that emit high-frequency pulses and listening for echoes, used for detecting water waves and water level, as in tide gauges or for towing tanks.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] To coordinate a series of large-scale observations, most sensing systems depend on the following: platform location and the orientation of the sensor.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] High-end instruments now often use positional information from satellite navigation systems.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The rotation and orientation are often provided within a degree or two with electronic compasses.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Compasses can measure not just azimuth (i. e. degrees to magnetic north), but also altitude (degrees above the horizon), since the magnetic field curves into the Earth at different angles at different latitudes.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] More exact orientations require gyroscopic-aided orientation, periodically realigned by different methods including navigation from stars or known benchmarks.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] There are applications of gamma rays to mineral exploration through remote sensing.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] In 1972 more than $2 million were spent on remote sensing applications with gamma rays to mineral exploration.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Gamma rays are used to search for deposits of uranium.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] By observing radioactivity from potassium, porphyry copper deposits can be located.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] A high ratio of uranium to thorium has been found to be related to the presence of hydrothermal copper deposits.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Radiation patterns have also been known to occur above oil and gas fields, but some of these patterns were thought to be due to surface soils instead of oil and gas.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The quality of remote sensing data consists of its spatial, spectral, radiometric and temporal resolutions.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] – typically pixels may correspond to square areas ranging in side length from 1 to 1,000 metres (3.3 to 3,280.8 ft).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The bandwidth of the different frequency bands recorded – usually, this is related to the number of frequency bands recorded by the platform.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] spectrum, ranging from a spectral resolution of 0.7 to 2.1 μm.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The Hyperion sensor on Earth Observing-1 resolves 220 bands from 0.4 to 2.5 μm, with a spectral resolution of 0.10 to 0.11 μm per band.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The number of different intensities of radiation the sensor is able to distinguish.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Typically, this ranges from 8 to 14 bits, corresponding to 256 levels of the gray scale and up to 16,384 intensities or "shades" of colour, in each band.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The frequency of flyovers by the satellite or plane, and is only relevant in time-series studies or those requiring an averaged or mosaic image as in deforesting monitoring.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] This was first used by the intelligence community where repeated coverage revealed changes in infrastructure, the deployment of units or the modification/introduction of equipment.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Cloud cover over a given area or object makes it necessary to repeat the collection of said location.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] In order to create sensor-based maps, most remote sensing systems expect to extrapolate sensor data in relation to a reference point including distances between known points on the ground.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] This depends on the type of sensor used.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] For example, in conventional photographs, distances are accurate in the center of the image, with the distortion of measurements increasing the farther you get from the center.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Another factor is that of the platen against which the film is pressed can cause severe errors when photographs are used to measure ground distances.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The step in which this problem is resolved is called georeferencing and involves computer-aided matching of points in the image (typically 30 or more points per image) which is extrapolated with the use of an established benchmark, "warping" the image to produce accurate spatial data.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] As of the early 1990s, most satellite images are sold fully georeferenced.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] In addition, images may need to be radiometrically and atmospherically corrected.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Allows avoidance of radiometric errors and distortions.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The illumination of objects on the Earth's surface is uneven because of different properties of the relief.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] This factor is taken into account in the method of radiometric distortion correction.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Radiometric correction gives a scale to the pixel values, e. g. the monochromatic scale of 0 to 255 will be converted to actual radiance values.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] In rugged mountains, as a result of terrain, the effective illumination of pixels varies considerably.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] In a remote sensing image, the pixel on the shady slope receives weak illumination and has a low radiance value, in contrast, the pixel on the sunny slope receives strong illumination and has a high radiance value.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] For the same object, the pixel radiance value on the shady slope will be different from that on the sunny slope.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Additionally, different objects may have similar radiance values.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] These ambiguities seriously affected remote sensing image information extraction accuracy in mountainous areas.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] It became the main obstacle to the further application of remote sensing images.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The purpose of topographic correction is to eliminate this effect, recovering the true reflectivity or radiance of objects in horizontal conditions.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Elimination of atmospheric haze by rescaling each frequency band so that its minimum value (usually realised in water bodies) corresponds to a pixel value of 0.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The digitizing of data also makes it possible to manipulate the data by changing gray-scale values.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Interpretation is the critical process of making sense of the data.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Image Analysis is the recently developed automated computer-aided application that is in increasing use.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Object-Based Image Analysis (OBIA) is a sub-discipline of GI-Science devoted to partitioning remote sensing (RS) imagery into meaningful image-objects, and assessing their characteristics through spatial, spectral and temporal scale.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Old data from remote sensing is often valuable because it may provide the only long-term data for a large extent of geography.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] At the same time, the data is often complex to interpret, and bulky to store.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Modern systems tend to store the data digitally, often with lossless compression.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The difficulty with this approach is that the data is fragile, the format may be archaic, and the data may be easy to falsify.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] One of the best systems for archiving data series is as computer-generated machine-readable ultrafiche, usually in typefonts such as OCR-B, or as digitized half-tone images.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Ultrafiches survive well in standard libraries, with lifetimes of several centuries.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] They can be created, copied, filed and retrieved by automated systems.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] They are about as compact as archival magnetic media, and yet can be read by human beings with minimal, standardized equipment.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The common analogy given to describe this is trying to determine the type of animal from its footprints.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] For example, while it is impossible to directly measure temperatures in the upper atmosphere, it is possible to measure the spectral emissions from a known chemical species (such as carbon dioxide) in that region.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The frequency of the emissions may then be related via thermodynamics to the temperature in that region.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] A Level 1 data record is the most fundamental (i. e., highest reversible level) data record that has significant scientific utility, and is the foundation upon which all subsequent data sets are produced.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Level 2 is the first level that is directly usable for most scientific applications; its value is much greater than the lower levels.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Level 2 data sets tend to be less voluminous than Level 1 data because they have been reduced temporally, spatially, or spectrally.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Level 3 data sets are generally smaller than lower level data sets and thus can be dealt with without incurring a great deal of data handling overhead.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] These data tend to be generally more useful for many applications.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The regular spatial and temporal organization of Level 3 datasets makes it feasible to readily combine data from different sources.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] While these processing levels are particularly suitable for typical satellite data processing pipelines, other data level vocabularies have been defined and may be appropriate for more heterogeneous workflows.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Satellite images provide very useful information to produce statistics on topics closely related to the territory, such as agriculture, forestry or land cover in general.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The first large project to apply Landsata 1 images for statistics was LACIE (Large Area Crop Inventory Experiment), run by NASA, NOAA and the USDA in 1974–77.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Many other application projects on crop area estimation have followed, including the Italian AGRIT project and the MARS project of the Joint Research Centre (JRC) of the European Commission.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] It is relevant to highlight that probabilistic sampling is not critical for the selection of training pixels for image classification, but it is necessary for accuracy assessment of the classified images and area estimation.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Additional care is recommended to ensure that training and validation datasets are not spatially correlated.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] We suppose now that we have classified images or a land cover map produced by visual photo-interpretation, with a legend of mapped classes that suits our purpose, taking again the example of wheat.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The straightforward approach is counting the number of pixels classified as wheat and multiplying by the area of each pixel.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The main strength of classified satellite images or other indicators computed on satellite images is providing cheap information on the whole target area or most of it.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] This information usually has a good correlation with the target variable (ground truth) that is usually expensive to observe in an unbiased and accurate way.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Therefore, it can be observed on a probabilistic sample selected on an area sampling frame.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Traditional survey methodology provides different methods to combine accurate information on a sample with less accurate, but exhaustive, data for a covariable or proxy that is cheaper to collect.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] For agricultural statistics, field surveys are usually required, while photo-interpretation may better for land cover classes that can be reliably identified on aerial photographs or high resolution satellite images.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Additional uncertainty can appear because of imperfect reference data (ground truth or similar).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] If we target other variables, such as crop yield or leaf area, we may need different indicators to be computed from images, such as the NDVI, a good proxy to chlorophyll activity.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Remote sensing of hydrologic processes can provide information on locations where *in situ* sensors may be unavailable or sparse.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] It also enables observations over large spatial extents.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Many of the variables constituting the terrestrial water balance, for example surface water storage, soil moisture, precipitation, evapotranspiration, and snow and ice, are measurable using remote sensing at various spatial-temporal resolutions and accuracies.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Sources of remote sensing include land-based sensors, airborne sensors and satellite sensors which can capture microwave, thermal and near-infrared data or use lidar, for example.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The modern discipline of remote sensing arose with the development of flight.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Tournachon (alias Nadar) made photographs of Paris from his balloon in 1858.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Messenger pigeons, kites, rockets and unmanned balloons were also used for early images.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] With the exception of balloons, these first, individual images were not particularly useful for map making or for scientific purposes.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Systematic aerial photography was developed for military surveillance and reconnaissance purposes beginning in World War I.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] After WWI, remote sensing technology was quickly adapted to civilian applications.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] A more recent development is that of increasingly smaller sensor pods such as those used by law enforcement and the military, in both manned and unmanned platforms.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The advantage of this approach is that this requires minimal modification to a given airframe.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Later imaging technologies would include infrared, conventional, Doppler and synthetic aperture radar.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The development of artificial satellites in the latter half of the 20th century allowed remote sensing to progress to a global scale as of the end of the Cold War.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Instrumentation aboard various Earth observing and weather satellites such as Landsat, the Nimbus and more recent missions such as RADARSAT and UARS provided global measurements of various data for civil, research, and military purposes.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Recent developments include, beginning in the 1960s and 1970s, the development of image processing of satellite imagery.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The use of the term "remote sensing" began in the early 1960s when Evelyn Pruitt realized that advances in science meant that aerial photography was no longer an adequate term to describe the data streams being generated by new technologies.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] With assistance from her fellow staff member at the Office of Naval Research, Walter Bailey, she coined the term "remote sensing".
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Several research groups in Silicon Valley including NASA Ames Research Center, GTE, and ESL Inc. developed Fourier transform techniques leading to the first notable enhancement of imagery data.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] In 1999 the first commercial satellite (IKONOS) collecting very high resolution imagery was launched.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Remote sensing has a growing relevance in the modern information society.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] It represents a key technology as part of the aerospace industry and bears increasing economic relevance – new sensors e.g.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] TerraSAR-X and RapidEye are developed constantly and the demand for skilled labour is increasing steadily.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Furthermore, remote sensing exceedingly influences everyday life, ranging from weather forecasts to reports on climate change or natural disasters.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] As an example, 80% of the German students use the services of Google Earth; in 2006 alone the software was downloaded 100 million times.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] But studies have shown that only a fraction of them know more about the data they are working with.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] There exists a huge knowledge gap between the application and the understanding of satellite images.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Remote sensing only plays a tangential role in schools, regardless of the political claims to strengthen the support for teaching on the subject.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] A lot of the computer software explicitly developed for school lessons has not yet been implemented due to its complexity.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Thereby, the subject is either not at all integrated into the curriculum or does not pass the step of an interpretation of analogue images.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] In fact, the subject of remote sensing requires a consolidation of physics and mathematics as well as competences in the fields of media and methods apart from the mere visual interpretation of satellite images.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Many teachers have great interest in the subject "remote sensing", being motivated to integrate this topic into teaching, provided that the curriculum is considered.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] In many cases, this encouragement fails because of confusing information.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] In order to integrate remote sensing in a sustainable manner organizations like the EGU or Digital Earth encourage the development of learning modules and learning portals.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Examples include: *FIS – Remote Sensing in School Lessons*, *Geospektiv*, *Ychange*, or Spatial Discovery, to promote media and method qualifications as well as independent learning.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Remote sensing data are processed and analyzed with computer software, known as a remote sensing application.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] A large number of proprietary and open source applications exist to process remote sensing data.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] An Earth observation satellite or Earth remote sensing satellite is a satellite used or designed for Earth observation (EO) from orbit, including spy satellites and similar ones intended for non-military uses such as environmental monitoring, meteorology, cartography and others.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The most common type are Earth imaging satellites, that take satellite images, analogous to aerial photographs; some EO satellites may perform remote sensing without forming pictures, such as in GNSS radio occultation.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The first occurrence of satellite remote sensing can be dated to the launch of the first artificial satellite, Sputnik 1, by the Soviet Union on October 4, 1957.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Sputnik 1 sent back radio signals, which scientists used to study the ionosphere.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The United States Army Ballistic Missile Agency launched the first American satellite, Explorer 1, for NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory on January 31, 1958.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The information sent back from its radiation detector led to the discovery of the Earth's Van Allen radiation belts.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The TIROS-1 spacecraft, launched on April 1, 1960, as part of NASA's Television Infrared Observation Satellite (TIROS) program, sent back the first television footage of weather patterns to be taken from space.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] In 2008, more than 150 Earth observation satellites were in orbit, recording data with both passive and active sensors and acquiring more than 10 terabits of data daily.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] By 2021, that total had grown to over 950, with the largest number of satellites operated by US-based company Planet Labs.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Most Earth observation satellites carry instruments that should be operated at a relatively low altitude.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Most orbit at altitudes above 500 to 600 kilometers (310 to 370 mi).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] Lower orbits have significant air-drag, which makes frequent orbit reboost maneuvers necessary.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The Earth observation satellites ERS-1, ERS-2 and Envisat of European Space Agency as well as the MetOp spacecraft of EUMETSAT are all operated at altitudes of about 800 km (500 mi).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The Proba-1, Proba-2 and SMOS spacecraft of European Space Agency are observing the Earth from an altitude of about 700 km (430 mi).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The Earth observation satellites of UAE, DubaiSat-1 & DubaiSat-2 are also placed in Low Earth orbits (LEO) orbits and providing satellite imagery of various parts of the Earth.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] To get global coverage with a low orbit, a polar orbit is used.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] A low orbit will have an orbital period of about 100 minutes and the Earth will rotate around its polar axis about 25° between successive orbits.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] The ground track moves towards the west 25° each orbit, allowing a different section of the globe to be scanned with each orbit.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] A geostationary orbit, at 36,000 km (22,000 mi), allows a satellite to hover over a constant spot on the earth since the orbital period at this altitude is 24 hours.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] This allows uninterrupted coverage of more than 1/3 of the Earth per satellite, so three satellites, spaced 120° apart, can cover the whole Earth.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/remote-sensing] This type of orbit is mainly used for meteorological satellites.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The first images from space were taken on sub-orbital flights.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The US-launched V-2 flight on October 24, 1946, took one image every 1.5 seconds.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] With an apogee of 65 miles (105 km), these photos were from five times higher than the previous record, the 13.7 miles (22 km) by the Explorer II balloon mission in 1935.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The first satellite (orbital) photographs of Earth were made on August 14, 1959, by the U.S.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The first satellite photographs of the Moon might have been made on October 6, 1959, by the Soviet satellite Luna 3, on a mission to photograph the far side of the Moon.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The Blue Marble photograph was taken from space in 1972, and has become very popular in the media and among the public.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Also in 1972 the United States started the Landsat program, the largest program for acquisition of imagery of Earth from space.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] In 1977, the first real time satellite imagery was acquired by the United States' KH-11 satellite system.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The most recent Landsat satellite, Landsat 9, was launched on 27 September 2021.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] All satellite images produced by NASA are published by NASA Earth Observatory and are freely available to the public.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Several other countries have satellite imaging programs, and a collaborative European effort launched the ERS and Envisat satellites carrying various sensors.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] There are also private companies that provide commercial satellite imagery.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] In the early 21st century satellite imagery became widely available when affordable, easy to use software with access to satellite imagery databases was offered by several companies and organizations.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Satellite images have numerous applications in a variety of fields.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Less mainstream uses include anomaly hunting, a criticized investigation technique involving the search of satellite images for unexplained phenomena.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The spectrum of satellite images includes visible light, near-infrared light, infrared light and radar, and many others.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] This wide range of light frequencies can provide researchers with large volumes of information.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] In addition to the satellite applications mentioned above, this data can serve as educational tools, advance scientific research and grow a deeper understanding of our environment.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Satellite images are used in many fields of activity — agriculture, geological and hydrological research, forestry, environmental protection, territorial planning, educational, intelligence and military purposes.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Such images can be made in the visible part of the spectrum, as well as in the ultraviolet, infrared and other parts of the range.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] There are also various terrain maps made using radar surveys.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Currently, the decryption and analysis of satellite images is increasingly performed using automated software systems such as ERDAS Imagine or ENVI.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] At the beginning of the development of this industry, some of the types of image enhancements commissioned by the US government were performed by contractor firms.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] For example, ESL Incorporated has developed one of the first two-dimensional Fourier transforms for digital image processing.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Satellite image analysis is actively used to protect the environment, for example, the "Visual satellite search for illegal landfills" method has identified more than 200 unauthorized municipal solid and household waste landfills on the territory of 5 subjects of the Russian Federation,.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] In France, satellite imagery has been used to spot private swimming pools, limiting evasion from a tax on swimming pools.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The purchase of private imagery is also a common practice among the open-source intelligence (or OSINT) community.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] For example, it enables the estimation of the remaining soviet military hardware in storage that can be refitted in the context of the War in Ukraine.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Because the total area of the land on Earth is so large and because resolution is relatively high, satellite databases are huge and image processing (creating useful images from the raw data) is time-consuming.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Preprocessing, such as image destriping, is often required.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Depending on the sensor used, weather conditions can affect image quality.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] For example, it is difficult to obtain images for areas of frequent cloud cover such as mountaintops.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] For such reasons, publicly available satellite image datasets are typically processed for visual or scientific commercial use by third parties.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Commercial satellite companies do not place their imagery into the public domain and do not sell their imagery; instead, one must acquire a license to use their imagery.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Thus, the ability to legally make derivative works from commercial satellite imagery is diminished.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Privacy concerns have been brought up by some who wish not to have their property shown from above.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Google Maps responds to such concerns in their FAQ with the following statement: "We understand your privacy concerns...
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] There are five types of resolution when discussing satellite imagery in remote sensing: spatial, spectral, temporal, radiometric and geometric.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The resolution of satellite images varies depending on the instrument used and the altitude of the satellite's orbit.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] For example, the Landsat archive offers repeated imagery at 30 meter resolution for the planet, but most of it has not been processed from the raw data.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Landsat 7 has an average return period of 16 days.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] For many smaller areas, images with resolution as fine as 41 cm can be available.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Satellite imagery is sometimes supplemented with aerial photography, which has higher resolution, but is more expensive per square meter.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Satellite imagery can be combined with vector or raster data in a GIS provided that the imagery has been spatially rectified so that it will properly align with other data sets.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Satellite imaging of the Earth surface is of sufficient public utility that many countries maintain satellite imaging programs.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The United States has led the way in making these data freely available for scientific use.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Some of the more popular programs are listed below, recently followed by the European Union's Sentinel constellation.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The *CORONA* program was a series of American strategic reconnaissance satellites produced and operated by the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) Directorate of Science & Technology with substantial assistance from the U.S.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The type of imagery is wet film panoramic and it used two cameras (AFT&FWD) for capturing stereographic imagery.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The ESA is currently developing the *Sentinel* constellation of satellites.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Currently, 7 missions are planned, each for a different application.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Sentinel-1 (SAR imaging), Sentinel-2 (decameter optical imaging for land surfaces), and Sentinel-3 (hectometer optical and thermal imaging for land and water) have already been launched.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The *ASTER* is an imaging instrument onboard Terra, the flagship satellite of NASA's Earth Observing System (EOS) launched in December 1999.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] ASTER is a cooperative effort between NASA, Japan's Ministry of Economy, Trade and Industry (METI), and Japan Space Systems (J-spacesystems).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] ASTER data is used to create detailed maps of land surface temperature, reflectance, and elevation.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The coordinated system of EOS satellites, including Terra, is a major component of NASA's Science Mission Directorate and the Earth Science Division.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The goal of NASA Earth Science is to develop a scientific understanding of the Earth as an integrated system, its response to change, and to better predict variability and trends in climate, weather, and natural hazards.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The *Meteosat*-2 geostationary weather satellite began operationally to supply imagery data on 16 August 1981.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Eumetsat has operated the Meteosats since 1987.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The Himawari satellite series features advanced imaging technology and frequent data updates.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Himawari-8 and Himawari-9 have become indispensable tools for weather forecasting, disaster management, and climate research, benefiting not only Japan but the entire Asia-Pacific region.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Several satellites are built and maintained by private companies, as follows.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] GeoEye's GeoEye-1 satellite was launched on September 6, 2008.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The GeoEye-1 satellite has high resolution imaging system and is able to collect images with a ground resolution of 0.41 meters (16 inches) in panchromatic or black and white mode.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] It collects multispectral or color imagery at 1.65-meter resolution or about 64 inches.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Maxar's WorldView-2 satellite provides high resolution commercial satellite imagery with 0.46 m spatial resolution (panchromatic only).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The 0.46 meters resolution of WorldView-2's panchromatic images allows the satellite to distinguish between objects on the ground that are at least 46 cm apart.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Similarly Maxar's QuickBird satellite provides 0.6 meter resolution (at nadir) panchromatic images.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Maxar's WorldView-3 satellite provides high resolution commercial satellite imagery with 0.31 m spatial resolution.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] WVIII also carries a short wave infrared sensor and an atmospheric sensor.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The 3 SPOT satellites in orbit (Spot 5, 6, 7) provide very high resolution images – 1.5 m for Panchromatic channel, 6m for Multi-spectral (R,G,B,NIR).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Spot Image also distributes multiresolution data from other optical satellites, in particular from Formosat-2 (Taiwan) and Kompsat-2 (South Korea) and from radar satellites (TerraSar-X, ERS, Envisat, Radarsat).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Spot Image is also the exclusive distributor of data from the high resolution Pleiades satellites with a resolution of 0.50 meter or about 20 inches.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The launches occurred in 2011 and 2012, respectively.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The company also offers infrastructures for receiving and processing, as well as added value options.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Planet Labs operates three satellite imagery constellations, RapidEye, Dove and SkySat.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] In 2015, Planet acquired BlackBridge, and its constellation of five RapidEye satellites, launched in August 2008.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The RapidEye constellation contains identical multispectral sensors which are equally calibrated.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Therefore, an image from one satellite will be equivalent to an image from any of the other four, allowing for a large amount of imagery to be collected (4 million km2 per day), and daily revisit to an area.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Each travel on the same orbital plane at 630 km, and deliver images in 5 meter pixel size.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] RapidEye satellite imagery is especially suited for agricultural, environmental, cartographic and disaster management applications.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The company not only offers their imagery, but consults their customers to create services and solutions based on analysis of this imagery.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The RapidEye constellation was retired by Planet in April 2020.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] SkySat is a constellation of sub-metre resolution Earth observation satellites that provide imagery, high-definition video and analytics services.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Planet acquired the satellites with their purchase of Terra Bella (formerly Skybox Imaging), a Mountain View, California-based company founded in 2009 by Dan Berkenstock, Julian Mann, John Fenwick, and Ching-Yu Hu, from Google in 2017.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The SkySat satellites are based on using inexpensive automotive grade electronics and fast commercially available processors, but scaled up to approximately the size of a minifridge.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The satellites are approximately 80 centimetres (31 in) long, compared to approximately 30 centimetres (12 in) for a 3U CubeSat, and weigh 100 kilograms (220 lb).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] Earth Resource Observation Satellites, better known as "EROS" satellites, are lightweight, low earth orbiting, high-resolution satellites designed for fast maneuvering between imaging targets.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] In the commercial high-resolution satellite market, EROS is the smallest very high resolution satellite; it is very agile and thus enables very high performances.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The satellites are deployed in a circular Sun-synchronous near polar orbit at an altitude of 510 km (± 40 km).
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] EROS A – a high resolution satellite with 1.9–1.2m resolution panchromatic was launched on December 5, 2000.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] EROS B – the second generation of Very High Resolution satellites with 70 cm resolution panchromatic, was launched on April 25, 2006.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] EROS C2 – the third generation of Very High Resolution satellites with 30 cm. resolution panchromatic, was launched in 2021.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] EROS C3 – the third generation of Very High Resolution satellites with 30 cm. resolution panchromatic and multispectral, was launched in 2023.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] GaoJing-1 / SuperView-1 (01, 02, 03, 04) is a commercial constellation of Chinese remote sensing satellites controlled by China Siwei Surveying and Mapping Technology Co.
[src:crop-monitoring-remote/satellite-imagery] The four satellites operate from an altitude of 530 km and are phased 90° from each other on the same orbit, providing 0.5m panchromatic resolution and 2m multispectral resolution on a swath of 12 km.
